sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: CreA
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Amino Half of Cre Recombinase (aka CreA)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The amino half of the Cre recombinase gene (BBa_J61047) was cloned into plasmid pSB1A2. This half contains the first 570 base pairs in the gene. The carboxyl half (BBa_I7165) of the Cre recombinase gene was also cloned into plasmid pSB1A2 and contains the remaining 462 base pairs of the gene. Our eventual goal was to insert a hixC site in the middle of the gene while maintaining Cre recombinase's functionality. The location of our split site was chosen based off of outside literature in which Cre Recombinase had been successfully split as well as the protein structure of Cre recombinase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Will DeLoache

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: hixC
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: hixC binding site for Salmonella typhimurium Hin recombinase
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: A 26 bp sequence of DNA composed of 12 bp inverted repeats and a 2 bp core that operates in Salmonella paired with a hixR binding site to recombine DNA. A second hix site is required for recombination to occur. The two sites bind Hin recombinase in the formation of an invertasome.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Missouri Western and Davidson Groups, Todd Eckdahl
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Nanassy and Hughes. 1998. In Vivo Identification of Intermediate Stages of the DNA Inversion Reaction Catlyzed by the Salmonella Hin Recombinase [http://www.genetics.org/cgi/content/abstract/149/4/1649]
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Standard BioBrick prefix and suffix were added to the 26 bp sequence.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: CreB
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Carboxl Half of Cre Recombinase (aka CreB)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The carboxyl half of the Cre recombinase gene (BBa_J61047) was cloned into plasmid pSB1A2. This half contains the last 462 base pairs in the gene. The amino half (BBa_I716500) of the Cre recombinase gene was also cloned into plasmid pSB1A2 and contains the first 570 base pairs of the gene. Our eventual goal is to insert a hixC site in the middle of the gene while maintaining Cre recombinase's functionality. The location of our split site was chosen based off of outside literature that demonstrated the successful splitting of Cre Recombinase, as well as the protein structure of Cre recombinase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Will DeLoache
